{"questionId":"21295","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, deduce that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>ω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>(since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ω</mi></math>&nbsp;is a root of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msup><mi>ω</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ω</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msup><mi>ω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> In part (a), award marks as appropriate where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ω</mi></math>&nbsp;has been converted into&nbsp;Cartesian, modulus-argument (polar) or Euler form.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21295","referenceCode":"21M.3.AHL.TZ2.2a.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, deduce that ω2+ω+1=0.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.12—Complex numbers – Cartesian form and Argand diag","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}